ğŸ Python Introduction
ğŸ“Œ What is Python?

Python was created in 1991 with a strong focus on code readability and the ability to express concepts using fewer lines of code.
It is a high-level, interpreted programming language widely used across various domains.

ğŸ”¹ Key Features of Python

Simple and easy-to-read syntax

Variables are automatically typed at runtime (Dynamic Typing)

Reduces code complexity and development time

Beginner-friendly yet powerful

ğŸ”¹ Programming Paradigms Supported

Python supports multiple programming styles:

Object-Oriented Programming (OOP)

Functional Programming

Procedural Programming

This flexibility makes Python suitable for different use cases and project requirements.

ğŸ–¨ï¸ Print Statement

The print() function is used to display output or text on the screen.

Example:
print("Hello World")

Explanation:

print() is a built-in Python function

It instructs the computer to display the given text or result on the screen

ğŸ’¬ Comments in Python

Comments are used to explain code and make it more readable.
They are ignored by the Python interpreter during execution.

ğŸ”¹ Single-Line Comment
# This is a single-line comment

ğŸ”¹ Multi-Line Comment

Python does not have a dedicated multi-line comment syntax, but we commonly use:

'''
This is a multi-line comment.
It can be used to describe larger sections of code.
'''


or

"""
This is a multi-line comment.
It can be used to describe larger sections of code.
"""

ğŸ“ Indentation in Python

Indentation is mandatory in Python and is used to define code blocks.

âœ… Correct Indentation
print("Hello")

âŒ Incorrect Indentation (Will cause an error)
    print("Hello")


ğŸ‘‰ Improper indentation results in an IndentationError.

âœ… Summary

Python emphasizes readability and simplicity

Uses dynamic typing

Supports multiple programming paradigms

print() displays output

Comments improve code readability

Indentation is crucial for program structure